The Venezuelan Government has maintained a system of currency controls since February 2003 with dual or multiple fixed and/or adjustable official exchange rates structure. Under this system, currency restrictions are applicable to all transactions in foreign currency, which includes exports and imports of goods and services and financial and capital transactions.&nbsp;
As a feature of the complex exchange arrangements, there are controls for current account transactions, payments for invisible and current transfers transactions, repatriation proceeds from exports and foreign direct investments (capital and dividends), for capital market securities, money market, collective investment securities and derivatives, commercial and financial credits, guarantees, financial backup facilities, personal capital transactions and specific provisions to commercial banks and other credit institutions and for institutional investors.&nbsp;
The system has in place two official mechanisms, the Protected Exchange Rate (DIPRO)&nbsp;and the&nbsp;Complementary Exchange System (DICOM) from March 2016, and DICOM updated on May 2017 (Forex Regulation N&ordm; 38) to provide companies and individual&rsquo;s access to foreign currency. As previous mechanisms, each one has a different exchange rate for foreign currencies, mainly the US dollar (USD) per bolivars (VEF), depending on the priority of the products and the purpose of the transaction. DIPRO is a primary exchange rate of VEF/USD 10 that applies only to essential imports, such as medicines and food, as well raw materials for production, pensions for Venezuelans living abroad, and national students at academic institutions abroad. This market covers 93% of the exchange operations on daily basis and it is administrated by Foreign Trade Centre (CENCOEX). In contrast, DICOM feeds only 7% residual of the exchange market and it is administrated by Central Bank of Venezuela (BCV) with a controlled floating exchange rate that applies for all non-essential imports.&nbsp;
The procedure for obtaining foreign currency under DIPRO continues to be very burdensome. Due the officially available foreign currency is far less than the demand a considerable number of companies have arrears with their suppliers abroad and therefore are lacking inputs for their production.&nbsp;
Also foreign investors in Venezuela are facing problems to convert their local earnings into USD or EUR. Venezuela have had six different exchange systems, some of them superposed, under the Foreign Exchange Control still in force during its 14 years of operation (CADIVI, SITME, SICAD I, SICAD II, SIMADI and from March 09, 2016 DIPRO-DICOM) which limits seriously the investor access to the very restricted foreign currency markets and with complex barriers for investors to handle.&nbsp;
The current regime, the Complementary Exchange System (DICOM) that works with a floating rate, was updated in May 2017 to operate through 8 currency auctions a month. The offer of each auction has been around USD 25M, adapted to the low liquidity of the Central Bank. The price of bidding was set, initially, in a fixed range between 1,800 to 2,200 VEF/USD, but it was rapidly increased to 2,010-2,640 (16 June 2017). Further adjustments to devaluation pressures might be expected for the near future.

