In framework of Exchange Control Regime in force since 2003 is required the presentation of the Non Production or Insufficiency of National Production Certificate for the achievement of formalities regarding imports at Foreign Trade Centre (CENCOEX) and also with Integrated Customs and Tax Administration Service (SENIAT)&nbsp;
The Non Production or Insufficiency of National Production Certificates are required by CENCOEX to apply for acquisition (ADD) and settlement (ALD) of preferential foreign exchanges intended to import goods consumer, industrials, raw materials and exoneration of customs taxes for these merchandise to SENIAT.&nbsp;
The "Certificate of Non National Production" applies where the merchandise is not available in national territory, while the "Certificate of Underproduction" is required when the merchandise assumed to be insufficient to supply the domestic market.&nbsp;
The way to obtain these certificates entails an extensive list of requirements, which are required by issuer's ministries, depending of the goods that are going to be imported. The procedure is so complex and discretional that has limited severely the foreign trade.&nbsp;
The approval and granting of the Certificate also does not necessarily imply authorization of the requested import quantities. Most of the time, import quantities are substantially lower than the requests made.&nbsp;
Certificates are valid for six (6) months from the date of issue and the amounts specified therein, what also constitutes a quantitative restriction on trade. Each user is expected to perform one (1) request per semester (not boarding), adding in the same plan all the imported products into that time frame.&nbsp;
Official Gazette N&ordm; 39.980 of August 7, 2012, establishes that only 1.013 Tariff Codes do not require the certificate of Non Production (List 1), which basically only apply to some food products and essential medicines, while the number of tariff codes that require the certificates (list 2) reaches 5.881 (5,8 times higher).

Restrictions to foreign direct investment were introduced under the Finance Law 2009 (LFC 2009, a mid-year supplementary budget law) on 26 July 2009 and were further strengthened through the Finance Law 2014. The recent Investment Code of 3 August 2016 introduces a few relevant modifications and no longer features the FEC (or "51/49 rule"), which continues nonetheless to apply by virtue of the Finance Laws of 2009 and 2014.&nbsp;
These measures, which have the effect of deterring foreign direct investment, include the following provisions:
- generalised limitations on foreign ownership: minimum Algerian shareholding of 51 % for all sectors;
- any foreign investment exceeding 5 billion DZD must be approved by the National Investment Council;
- foreign investors must maintain a positive foreign-currency account for the whole duration of the investment and must secure the finance to cover project costs from local sources;
There are also some restrictions (more de facto than de jure, it seems) to the transfer of benefits generated through foreign investment. The financial transfers outside Algeria are an obstacle not only from the FDI perspective, but also with regard to commercial activities. One particular aspect of this general obstacle is illustrated by the difficulties encountered by the ship-owners, who have not been able since 2010 to repatriate credits deposited on their disbursement accounts whenever these credits accrued to the accounts after a period of 90 days of arrival of the goods. This problem has now been solved for future transactions by allowing the opening of complementary disbursement accounts for any payment effected after the initial 90 days of the arrival of the goods. However, the Algerian authorities are yet to allow ship-owners to transfer pre-existing credits, which accrued under the old regulation.
There are indications that the Government may be considering amending further the 51/49 rule and limiting its scope of application to certain sectors only (while stopping short of repealing the rule altogether).

A number of ongoing market barriers are affecting the automotive sector exports to Colombia, including discriminatory internal taxes; developing biofuel policies; scrapping policies for trucks and a serie of technical regulations requiring re-certification in Colombia.&nbsp;&nbsp;
Technical Regulations:
The Resolution of Ministry of Transport No. 3753 (6 October 2015) introduces a technical regulation for the vehicles in public service of passengers (with capacity above 9 persons) which stipulates the obligation to comply with the system of certifications. Thus the local producers and importers have to obtain, before the sale of the vehicles, a certificate of conformity. The Resolution entered into force on 6 October 2016.

The&nbsp;Decret No. 1517 was published on 22 September&nbsp;2016 as amendment to Decree No. 1079, providing provisions on a transition mechanism&nbsp;for elimination of the ''1 for 1'' system for scrappage and a more free entry of new vehicles in the market.&nbsp;According to the Decree, the ''1 for 1 ''rule should be phased out by 31 December 2018, &nbsp;opening the door&nbsp;to a free market access for imports of heavy trucks of above 10,5 t. Moreover, it stipulates more transparency in the administration of permits of new vehicle registrations which should rom ow on be managed by the Transport Ministry. However, the truckers' sector criticised the Decree upon its publication denouncing the absence of any consultation with this sector in the drafting process.&nbsp; Ahead of an imminent threat of another&nbsp;strike Colombia started negotiations with the truckers and will probably elaborate&nbsp;the final legislation/legal regulation for the current Decree with them.&nbsp;A succesful implementation of the Decree is crucial&nbsp;for the accession process of Colombia to OECD.&nbsp;
The Decree 1517 was preceeded by several attempts by the Government to dismantle the discriminatory system which has been practically blocking imports of heavy trucks and suffered from vast corruption.
On 16 August 2013, Colombia issued the decree 1760 (which amended previous decree 2085 of 2008). Decree 2085 of 2008 stipulated that a new truck can only be registered if another vehicle corresponding to the same weight capacity (or several trucks corresponding in total to the same weight capacity) is physically scrapped or if a fee (in 2008 this corresponded to US$ 10.000 to 30.000) depending on the type of truck, is paid. The new decree 1760 eliminated the fee option, therefore restricting the import of a new truck by making it subject to the scrapping of an old one.
The scrappage scheme has been in place since 2003. Meanwhile, the EU together wth other partners (U.S., Mexico) has been pushing for the elimination of this barrier to trade in the car sector.&nbsp;

