It appears that the Thai Liquor Act discriminates against imported spirits in favour of local ones in various aspects. Local white spirits are taxed at a lower rate than imported white spirits.&nbsp; Some local fruit wines (made from grape wine imported in bulk with minor addition of other fruit juice, bottled/packaged and marketed similarly to grape wine) are subject to a lower excise tax rate than regular imported grape wine. Additionally, wines with last wholesale price higher than 600 baht/bottle are subject to excise tax based on both ad valorem and specific basis while wines with last wholesale price of no more than 600 baht/bottle are only subject to specific excise tax. These factors allow the said local fruit wines to compete in the market at price advantage. Apart from the discriminatory excise tax, the sale license fee regime also discriminates against imported products.
&nbsp;
Currently, the Liquor Act is being made an integral part of the Excise Tax Code, which will combine all different excise tax laws into a single Act and will harmonise tax base at ''suggested retail price''. For alcohol products, the draft Excise Tax Code also indicates a move towards specific tax rates by imposing much higher specific tax ceilings and lower ad valorem tax ceilings. According to the draft Act, the discrimination in sale license fees will be eliminated. Based on our discussion with the Excise Tax Department, the discrimination in tax rates between local fruit wines and imported grape wines will be eliminated while the discrimination in tax rates between local white spirits and imported ones will be maintained. However, the price threshold system in wine will be maintained (adjusting from last whole sale price to suggested retail price) and the system may be extended to other spirits. Whether this would continue to constitute/increase discrimination or not would depend on the levels of threshold.
&nbsp;

The Foreign Business Act 1999 (FBA) lays out the overall framework governing foreign investment in Thailand. The FBA sets out a maximum of 49 per cent limitation on foreign ownership in all service businesses (with only company-by-company provisional exemptions). In the past few years, Thailand attempted to tighten the law by adding new criteria used to qualify companies as foreign referring not only to ownership limitation but also to the majority of voting rights and management controls. In addition, the Thai authorities have put in place various harassment and tracking procedures implying obligations for companies with foreign shareholding of 40% and above to disclose the source of funding of Thai shareholders. Similar procedures are aimed at addressing specific problem of the acquisition of land by foreigners. Furthermore, EU investors are put at a disadvantage vis-&agrave;-vis U.S. investors who still benefit from national treatment provisions in the US-Thailand Treaty of Amity 1968 with regard to establishing and acquiring interests in enterprises of all types for engaging in commercial, industrial, financial and other business activities, with the exception of a few sectors (inland transportation and communication industries, banking involving depository functions, fiduciary functions, business of inland communication, domestic trade in indigenous agricultural products and exploiting land or other natural resources), although the WTO derogation from Art. II GATS (MFN-clause) expired at the end of 2004 (after 10 years).
&nbsp;
Apart from the FBA, a number of service sectors are also regulated by sectoral laws under respective regulators e.g. insurance, banking, telecommunications, transport, etc. Regulators in certain sectors like insurance and banking, while maintaining a general rule on Thai majority ownership, still allow foreign majority ownership on a case-by-case basis. However, some regulators could be very protective e.g. in telecommunications where the regulator has introduced foreign dominance criteria (e.g. management control, using preferential stock with different voting rights to control, etc.) in addition to the equity ownership, which is the only general criterion in Thailand's GATS commitments. The regulator in civil aviation also plans to introduce foreign dominance criteria in air transport services similarly to the one in the telecommunications by October 2016. Thailand is free to regulate in the air transport services as there is no international commitment made on Mode 3 of the sector (except for some activities like maintenance or selling and marketing of air transport services). While these foreign dominance criteria have not had material impact on European business in the market, it will certainly have an impact on new entry.

