Country-wide ban due to avian influenza on some EU Member States despite that effective zoning (regionalisation)&nbsp;measures have been put in place. These EU measure put in place are in line with international standards and guarantee that safe trade can continue to take place.
Avian influenza (also named &ldquo;avian flu&rdquo; or &ldquo;bird flu&rdquo;) is a viral disease which occurs primarily in poultry and other birds. There are many different types of avian influenza viruses. Occasional outbreaks of avian influenza are seen in different countries in the world, including in the EU. Most of the outbreaks are caused by low pathogenicity avian influenza strains of the virus.&nbsp;At the end of 2014, highly pathogenic avian influenza was detected in several EU Member States.&nbsp; Immediate stringent measures were taken to prevent further spreading and to eradicate the disease.&nbsp; The EU measures taken have proven to be highly effective and guaranteed that no further spreading took place out of the well-defined affected areas so that trade could continue to take place in safe conditions in the non-affected areas. This EU regionalisation policy&nbsp; is striclty&nbsp; implemented in all EU Member States whenever an outbreak of avian influenza occurs.&nbsp;So-called zoning measures have been put immediately in place in the well-defined disease area (affected zone) which guarantees no further spreading of the virus to other parts within the European Union and to trading partners.&nbsp;
Trading partners should recognise this policy in line with their WTO obligations to minimise negative trade effects as safe trade can continue to take place and thus does not deserve a country-wide ban.

